"Lennartz S., Bunde A.","Trend evaluation in records with long-term memory: Application to global warming",2009,"Geophysical Research Letters","36","16", L16706,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL039516,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-71949125073&partnerID=40&md5=2a116f7542cf2e4870c92a2b018186f8","Institut für Theoretische Physik III, JustusLiebig-Universität Giessen, Heinrich-Buff-Ring 16, D-35392 Giessen, Germany","Lennartz, S., Institut für Theoretische Physik III, JustusLiebig-Universität Giessen, Heinrich-Buff-Ring 16, D-35392 Giessen, Germany; Bunde, A., Institut für Theoretische Physik III, JustusLiebig-Universität Giessen, Heinrich-Buff-Ring 16, D-35392 Giessen, Germany","Previous statistical detection methods indicate that, on a global scale, the observed warming cannot be attributed solely to natural fluctuations. Here we estimate the probability W(Δ) that an observed trend Δ occurs naturally, and determine the anthropogenic part A<inf>Q</inf>(Δ) of the temperature increase wimin a given confidence interval Q. To obtain these quantities, we do not use climate simulations, but assume as statistical null hypothesis that monthly temperature records are long-term correlated with a Hurst exponent α > 0.5 (including also nonstationary records with α values above 1). We show that for confidence intervals with Q above 80% analytical expressions for W(Δ) and A<inf>Q</inf>(Δ) can be derived, which request as input solely the Hurst exponent, as well as the temperature increase Δ obtained from the linear regression line and the standard deviation σ<inf>t</inf> around it. We apply this approach to global and local temperature data and discuss the different results. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Financial data processing; Global warming; Analytical expressions; Climate simulation; Confidence interval; Global scale; Hurst exponents; Local temperature; Long term memory; Natural fluctuations; Nonstationary; Null hypothesis; Standard deviation; Statistical detection; Temperature increase; Probability density function; anthropogenic effect; confidence interval; global warming; hypothesis testing; probability; regression analysis; temperature profile",,,,,,"Barnett, T., Detecting and attributing external influences on the climate system: A review of recent advances (2005) J. Clim., 18 (9), pp. 1291-1314; Bloomfield, P., Nychka, D., Climate spectra and detecting climate change (1992) Clim. Change, 21, pp. 275-287; Brohan, P., Kennedy, J.J., Harris, I., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, P.D., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed temperature changes: A new data set from 1850 (2006) Journal of Geophysical Research D: Atmospheres, 111 (12), pp. D12106. , DOI 10.1029/2005JD006548; Bunde, A., Eichner, J.F., Kantelhardt, J.W., Havlin, S., Longterm memory: A natural mechanism for the clustering of extreme events and anomalous residual times in climate records (2005) Phys. Rev. Lett., 94, p. 048701. , doi: 10.1103/PhysRevLett.94.048701; Cohn, T.A., Lins, H.F., Nature's style: Naturally trendy (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32, pp. L23402. , doi:10.1029/2005GL024476; Fraedrich, K., Blender, R., Scaling of atmosphere and ocean temperature correlations on observations and climate models (2003) Phys. Rev. Lett., 90, p. 108501. , doi:10.1103/PhysRevLett.90.108501; Halley, J.M., Using models with long-term persistence to interpret the rapid increase of Earth's temperature (2009) Physica A, 388, pp. 2492-2502. , doi:10.1016/j.physa.2009.02.027; Hasselmann, K., Optimal fingerprints for the detection of time-dependent climate change (1993) Journal of Climate, 6 (10), pp. 1957-1971; Hegerl, G.C., Von Stroch, H., Hasselmann, K., Santer, B.D., Cubasch, U., Jones, P.D., Detecting greenhouse-gas-induced climate change with an optimal fingerprint method (1996) Journal of Climate, 9 (10), pp. 2281-2306; Kantelhardt, J.W., Koscielny-Bunde, E., Rego, H.H.A., Havlin, S., Bunde, A., Detecting long-range correlations with detrended fluc